          "type": "plan",
          "text": "# Plan: research-only — getting `message_id → ranges` into the final authorship log\n\n## Status\nPhase 1 (research). Pivoted from \"reuse rebase logic\" to first understanding **how line ranges flow across the chain of working-log checkpoints on a normal commit**, before deciding how to add a parallel message-id stream.\n\n## How line ranges live across the working-log checkpoint chain (verified in code)\n\n### Per-checkpoint persistence — coordinates are local to each checkpoint\n- `WorkingLogEntry` (`working_log.rs:13-37`) holds for one file at one checkpoint:\n  - `blob_sha` — content hash *at this checkpoint*\n  - `attributions: Vec<Attribution>` — char positions in **this checkpoint's content**\n  - `line_attributions: Vec<LineAttribution>` — line numbers in **this checkpoint's content**\n  - `added_line_ranges`, `deleted_line_ranges`, `added_line_entries`, `deleted_line_entries` — diff against the previous checkpoint, in respective old/new coords\n- Each `WorkingLogEntry` is persisted **once**, in its own coordinates, and **never rewritten**.\n- Older checkpoints stay in their original coordinates forever.\n\n### Building a new checkpoint reads only the latest prior entry per file\n`build_previous_file_state_maps` (`commands/checkpoint.rs:1649-1674`) walks all prior checkpoints, but its `insert(...)` keeps only the **last** entry per file:\n```rust\nfor checkpoint in previous_checkpoints {\n    for entry in &checkpoint.entries {\n        previous_file_state_by_file.insert(entry.file.clone(),\n            PreviousFileState { blob_sha: entry.blob_sha.clone(),\n                                attributions: entry.attributions.clone() });\n    }\n}\n```\nSo checkpoint N+1's \"previous\" input is the last checkpoint that wrote that file — taken **as-is in those coords**, alongside the file content stored under that blob_sha.\n\n### Forward projection happens at checkpoint creation time\n`make_entry_for_file` (`commands/checkpoint.rs:2156-2248`):\n1. `attribute_unattributed_ranges(...)` fills any gaps in the previous attributions with `\"human\"`.\n2. `update_attributions_for_checkpoint(previous_content, content, prev_attrs, author_id, ts, is_ai_checkpoint)` runs imara-diff between previous_content and content, carries old `author_id` through preserved regions, stamps the new `author_id` on edited regions. **Output is char-level, in this checkpoint's new content coordinates.**\n3. `attributions_to_line_attributions_for_checkpoint(new_attrs, content, is_ai_checkpoint)` turns char→line, with line numbers from `LineBoundaries::new(content)` of *this* checkpoint's content.\n4. A fresh `WorkingLogEntry` is persisted with both streams in this checkpoint's coordinates.\n\nSo the answer to \"do line numbers get persisted then updated on each checkpoint?\" is: **No update in place. Each checkpoint persists its own coordinates and they stay frozen. The \"update\" is the projection that happens once when checkpoint N+1 reads N's persisted state to compute its own.**\n\n### Final aggregation — `from_just_working_log` (`virtual_attribution.rs:313-480`)\nWalks all checkpoints in order. For each entry:\n```rust\nlet line_attrs = if entry.line_attributions.is_empty() {\n    attributions_to_line_attributions(&entry.attributions, &file_content)\n} else {\n    entry.line_attributions.clone()\n};\n// ...\nattributions.insert(entry.file.clone(), (char_attrs, line_attrs));\n```\n- The `insert` **overwrites** — the last checkpoint that touched the file wins.\n- No cross-checkpoint replay here. Each checkpoint's persisted attributions are *already* in its own (and thus the latest, by induction) coordinates.\n\nSo the final commit's attestation = the **latest checkpoint's** persisted line attributions, grouped by `author_id` and emitted via `to_authorship_log()` (verified earlier).\n\n## The conversation_id vs message_id correction\n\nThe user pointed out (correctly):\n- A conversation has many user messages, each with their own range structure.\n- Within a single checkpoint, only one user message is responsible — so within a checkpoint, the conversation hash and the message id stamp the *same* newly-edited regions.\n- Across checkpoints, the conversation id stays constant but message id varies → final per-author ranges are unions of many per-message ranges → **the two have different range shapes**.\n\n### Why naively adding `message_id` to `LineAttribution` is awkward\n\n`LineAttribution` is currently produced with merging logic in `attributions_to_line_attributions` (`attribution_tracker.rs:2003-2077`) that **merges consecutive lines with the same `author_id`** into a single range. If we put `message_id` on the same struct and required matching on both fields to merge, the existing per-author merging would fragment (consecutive lines from the same conversation but different messages would no longer merge). Conversely, leaving merging keyed only on `author_id` and storing some \"winner\" `message_id` per merged block loses fidelity for any line whose latest message differs from its neighbors.\n\nThis matches the user's suggestion that **a parallel data stream** is cleaner than overloading the existing structs.\n\n## Three plausible designs (in order of invasiveness)\n\n### Design 1: parallel per-line message stream on `WorkingLogEntry`\nAdd a new field on `WorkingLogEntry`:\n```\npub message_line_attributions: Vec<MessageLineAttribution>\n```\nwhere `MessageLineAttribution { start_line, end_line, message_id, ts }`. Built and projected by an exact mirror of the existing pipeline:\n- At checkpoint creation, run a second imara-diff projection on a parallel `message_attributions: Vec<MessageAttribution>` char stream (or reuse the same diff plan; see Design 3).\n- Stamp the **current checkpoint's `user_prompt_id`** on newly-edited regions.\n- Carry old message_ids through preserved regions.\n- Merge consecutive line ranges by message_id (different merge boundaries from the conversation stream).\n\n`from_just_working_log` needs an analogous `message_attributions` field on `VirtualAttributions` (just take the last checkpoint's `message_line_attributions` per file). `to_authorship_log()` adds a parallel grouping loop emitting `Vec<FileMessageAttestation>`.\n\n**Pros**: clean separation; doesn't fragment the existing author-level merges. **Cons**: two parallel pipelines; storage roughly doubles for AI-edited files.\n\n### Design 2: derive message ranges from per-checkpoint diffs at aggregation time only\nDon't store anything new per-checkpoint. Instead, at `from_just_working_log` time, walk checkpoints in order; for each AI checkpoint, take the checkpoint's `added_line_ranges` and project them through *all subsequent checkpoints' diffs* (using `update_attributions`-style imara replay) into the final coords. Stamp those projected ranges with the checkpoint's `user_prompt_id`.\n\n**Pros**: zero schema change to working logs; works retroactively on existing data. **Cons**: O(checkpoints²) projections in worst case; complex; breaks naturally on rebase because old checkpoints' diffs are relative to old content states.\n\n### Design 3: shared imara projection, two outputs\nAt checkpoint creation, run imara-diff once but during the carry-through, populate two parallel attribution sets — one keyed by author, one keyed by message — with identical char-level ranges but different identifiers. Persist both.\n\n**Pros**: amortizes the diff cost; conceptually one operation. **Cons**: requires touching `update_attributions` to take/return two streams; bigger code surgery.\n\n## Open questions for user\n1. Is Design 1 (parallel stream on WorkingLogEntry, persisted per checkpoint) the right shape? Or would you rather avoid storing extra data on disk and recompute on demand?\n2. For \"latest message per line\", what's the granularity expectation when a human edits an AI line? E.g.: AI message M1 wrote line, human typed over it, then AI message M2 added a comment without changing the line. Does the line attribute to M1, M2, or \"human-overrode-M1\"?\n3. Should the new structure live on the working log JSONL (durable, survives across processes), or be transient (computed at post-commit only)?\n",
