          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## High-level changes\n\n### 1. New per-line message-id authorship stream\nA second attestation stream alongside the existing conversation-level one, keyed by `user_prompt_id` (the UUID of the user message that triggered the AI edit) instead of by conversation hash. Lets you ask \"which user message owns line N?\" instead of just \"which conversation?\".\n\n- **Working log** (`WorkingLogEntry`) gained `message_attributions` and `message_line_attributions` fields, parallel to the existing `attributions` / `line_attributions`.\n- **Per-checkpoint stamping** (`make_entry_for_file`) now stamps both streams in lockstep, using the same imara-diff projection machinery for both.\n- **VirtualAttributions** gained `message_attributions` and a `synthetic_msg_resolver` map, populated when reading the working log.\n- **AuthorshipLog** gained a `message_attestations: Vec<FileAttestation>` field, populated by `to_authorship_log` and `to_authorship_log_and_initial_working_log`.\n\n### 2. Late-resolved synthetic message ids\nCursor's SQLite often hasn't persisted the user-message id by the time the AI checkpoint hook fires. To avoid stamping the wrong id (or `None`), checkpoints stamp a *synthetic id* derived from `cp.diff` (`__cpdiff_<hash>`). At post-commit time — after `update_prompts_to_latest` backfills `cp.user_prompt_id` from a refreshed transcript — a `synthetic_msg_resolver` map (`__cpdiff_<hash> → user_prompt_id`) translates them to real ids before serialization. Synthetic ids never appear in published notes.\n\n### 3. Note format\nConversation attestation comes first, then (optionally) the message attestation block, then JSON metadata, separated by `---` dividers:\n```\n<conv attestation>\n---\n<msg attestation>     ← only when non-empty\n---                   ← only when msg block present\n{json metadata}\n```\nBackward compatible: notes without a message block use a single divider, exactly as before. The deserializer handles both shapes.\n\n### 4. Q2=a behavior — humans drop messages\nA `Human` or `KnownHuman` checkpoint stamps the `\"human\"` sentinel on the message stream. At attestation time those entries are filtered out, so any line whose latest editor was a human disappears from the message attestation. Mirrors the existing conversation-stream treatment of pure-human-edited lines.\n\n### 5. History rewriting (rebase / squash / amend)\nThe message stream is propagated through every history-rewriting path:\n- **`merge_attributions_favoring_first`** (CI squash, amend, force-push/reset): for each file, line-level message attributions on both sides are converted to char-level, projected to final-commit coordinates via the same imara-diff used for the conv stream, merged, and converted back. Synthetic resolvers from both sides are union-merged.\n- **`transform_attributions_to_final_state`** (cherry-pick / 1:1 rebase transform): mirrors the conv stream's char-level projection for the message stream and threads it through `new_with_prompts`.\n- **Hunk-based rebase fast path** (`try_reconstruct_attributions_from_notes_cached` + the per-commit replay loop): reads `log.message_attestations` from each prior commit's note, applies `apply_hunks_to_line_attributions` to shift line numbers, overlays each commit's stamps. A parallel `cached_file_message_attestation_text` cache is maintained per file. The note assembly emits the new layout with the message block between the two dividers.\n- **Blob-equivalent fast remap**: untouched — the byte-edit only updates `base_commit_sha` in JSON, and the message block sits before the JSON, so it rides along intact.\n\n### 6. New `git ai message-history` command\n`git ai message-history <file> <line> [--commit <sha>]` walks `git log -L<line>:<file>` and, for each commit that touched the line, looks up the user message that owned it at that commit. Output is JSON with one row per commit:\n- `commit_sha`, `commit_date`, `commit_message`, `target_line`\n- `line_content` — the line's exact text at that commit\n- `message` — `{ message_id, conversation_id, agent_type, model, text, timestamp }`, or `null` if the line was last edited by a human or the commit pre-dates the feature.\n\n### 7. Tests\nThree new lib unit tests in `virtual_attribution::tests` exercising the end-to-end pipeline:\n- Single AI checkpoint with a real `user_prompt_id` → attestation populated, round-trips through serialize/deserialize.\n- Multi-checkpoint scenario (M1 → human → human → M2 → human) with distinct message ids → asserts each line is correctly attributed.\n- Same-message-id case (both AI checkpoints share `user_prompt_id`) → asserts the line that's never re-stamped after the first checkpoint stays attributed.\n\nAll 1320 lib tests pass; `cargo build` clean.\n\n### Files touched\n- `src/authorship/working_log.rs` — `WorkingLogEntry` fields.\n- `src/authorship/attribution_tracker.rs` — (no struct changes; existing primitives reused).\n- `src/authorship/authorship_log_serialization.rs` — `AuthorshipLog.message_attestations`, `SYNTHETIC_MSG_PREFIX`, serializer/deserializer.\n- `src/authorship/virtual_attribution.rs` — `message_attributions`, `synthetic_msg_resolver`, the three `from_*_working_log` methods, `to_authorship_log`, `to_authorship_log_and_initial_working_log`, `merge_attributions_favoring_first`.\n- `src/authorship/rebase_authorship.rs` — `try_reconstruct_attributions_from_notes_cached` (return type extended), per-commit hunk loop, note assembly, `transform_attributions_to_final_state`.\n- `src/authorship/post_commit.rs` (no changes — gets the fix for free via `to_authorship_log_and_initial_working_log`).\n- `src/authorship/agent_detection.rs` and `src/authorship/range_authorship.rs` — minor: include the new `message_attestations: Vec::new()` field in struct-literal constructions.\n- `src/commands/checkpoint.rs` — `PreviousFileState`, `FileEntryInput`, `get_checkpoint_entries`, `get_checkpoint_entry_for_file`, `make_entry_for_file`, threading `combined_hash` and